Let X_\bullet  be a simplicial set.
    Denote by D(\Delta _n,\Delta _M) the set of increasing surjective maps from \Delta _n to \Delta _m (degeneracy operators), and set

    2553hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.1.xmlEquation6.2.1.1hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1         N(X_n)         = X_n\setminus \bigcup _{{s\in  D(\Delta _n,\Delta _{n-1})}}s(X_{n-1}).       \tag{6.2.1.1}

Recall that, for all n, the map

    2554hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1.2.xmlEquation6.2.1.2hodge-theory-iii-6.2.1         \coprod  s         \colon  \coprod _{\mathclap {\substack {m\leqslant  n,\\s\in  D(\Delta _n,\Delta _m)}}} N(X_m)         \to  X_n       \tag{6.2.1.2}       

    is bijective.

Using , we can show that, for every separated scheme S over \mathbb {C}, there exists:







        a simplicial scheme X_\bullet  over \mathbb {C}, smooth and proper, that we can take to be s-split;





        a normal crossing divisor D_\bullet  of X_\bullet ; we set U_\bullet =X_\bullet \setminus  D_\bullet ;





        an augmentation a\colon  U_\bullet \to  S that realises U_\bullet ^\mathrm {an} as a proper hypercover of S^\mathrm {an}.

Furthermore, any two such systems are covered by a third, and a morphism u\colon S\to T can be covered by a morphism
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} X_\bullet \ar [r] & Y_\bullet \\U_\bullet \ar [r] \ar [u,hook] \ar [d,swap,"a"] & V_\bullet \ar [u,hook] \ar [d,"b"] \\S \ar [r,swap,"u"] & T \end {tikzcd}
of such systems (see [SD]).

We take \mathscr {C} to be:






        the category of topological spaces and continuous maps, with final object e=P^t;





        the category of pairs (X,F) where X is a topological space and F is an abelian sheaf on X, with an arrow (u,f)\colon (Y,F)\to (X,G) consisting of a continuous map u\colon  Y\to  X and a u-morphism () f\colon  G\to  F, with final object e=(P^t,0).

Let u\colon Y_\bullet \to X_\bullet be a morphism of topological simplicial spaces, with cone C(u). Let F be an abelian sheaf on X_\bullet and G an abelian sheaf on Y_\bullet , and let f\colon G\to F be a u-morphism. The cone C(f) of f is an abelian sheaf on C(u), and we set
2655hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2.1.xmlEquation6.3.2.1hodge-theory-iii-6.3.2 \operatorname {H}^n(C(u),C(f)) = \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet \operatorname {mod} Y_\bullet , F\operatorname {mod} G). \tag{6.3.2.1}
These are the relative cohomology groups. We can easily show that they fit into a long exact sequence
